00:11:24.870 --> 00:11:27.450
Now, in fairness, it turns out
that RunKeeper has a new beta.

00:11:27.450 --> 00:11:31.460
So I'm going to switch to that,
which hopefully I took a

00:11:31.460 --> 00:11:34.500
screenshot of, but I
apparently didn't.

00:11:34.500 --> 00:11:36.610
Now, their new design is
definitely more modern.

00:11:36.610 --> 00:11:39.490
It's very much the
same navigation

00:11:39.490 --> 00:11:40.960
as you can see here.

00:11:40.960 --> 00:11:43.560
But they've replaced
the tabs with a

00:11:43.560 --> 00:11:45.710
ViewPager-style tab pager.

00:11:45.710 --> 00:11:46.710
They've got an action bar.

00:11:46.710 --> 00:11:49.090
Now, unfortunately, it looks
like a ViewPager, but it

00:11:49.090 --> 00:11:49.840
doesn't swipe.

00:11:49.840 --> 00:11:51.390
So that's one of the most
important things that they

00:11:51.390 --> 00:11:54.220
need to do to create that
consistency, is make sure that

00:11:54.220 --> 00:11:55.470
they can swipe between tabs.

00:11:58.210 --> 00:12:01.110
And that's kind of the story for
their entire redesign, is

00:12:01.110 --> 00:12:03.350
that it's not really a
change in the app.

00:12:03.350 --> 00:12:05.150
It's just cosmetic.

00:12:05.150 --> 00:12:07.500
So I would definitely suggest
that they take this

00:12:07.500 --> 00:12:10.300
opportunity to rethink some of
the navigation, some of the

00:12:10.300 --> 00:12:15.990
structure of the app, as well
as just the raw cosmetics.

00:12:15.990 --> 00:12:17.670
Because at the moment, the
layout and navigation is

00:12:17.670 --> 00:12:19.300
pretty much unchanged.

00:12:19.300 --> 00:12:21.380
And in terms of data and
functionality provided on the

00:12:21.380 --> 00:12:23.680
main screen, it's actually
pretty similar to what

00:12:23.680 --> 00:12:27.490
Endomondo has with a couple of
really important differences.

00:12:27.490 --> 00:12:30.490
Now, before I start exercising
there's no indication of what

00:12:30.490 --> 00:12:32.100
information I'll get.

00:12:32.100 --> 00:12:32.990
Will it be mapped?

00:12:32.990 --> 00:12:35.980
Will it be recording the
time or distance?

00:12:35.980 --> 00:12:39.170
I really don't see any of that
before I get started, and that

00:12:39.170 --> 00:12:43.840
really makes me reluctant to
get started in my exercise

00:12:43.840 --> 00:12:45.810
knowing that I really don't know
what's going to happen,

00:12:45.810 --> 00:12:48.860
how much of what I want to be
recorded is going to be.

00:12:48.860 --> 00:12:52.040
And a lot of users are like
me, and they'll install a

00:12:52.040 --> 00:12:54.910
bunch of options all at once
before jumping in and seeing

00:12:54.910 --> 00:12:56.410
what each has to offer.

00:12:56.410 --> 00:12:59.330
So as a result, it's important
that you give potential users

00:12:59.330 --> 00:13:02.510
as clear a picture of what you
offer without them having to

00:13:02.510 --> 00:13:04.391
do anything.

00:13:04.391 --> 00:13:07.290
Now, they've also put a lot of
emphasis on how I'm receiving

00:13:07.290 --> 00:13:08.150
my location.

00:13:08.150 --> 00:13:10.150
And the input type is the first
thing I'm presented

00:13:10.150 --> 00:13:13.460
with, and 99% of the time
that's going to be GPS,

00:13:13.460 --> 00:13:16.350
probably consolidated with Wi-Fi
and cell ID, if that's

00:13:16.350 --> 00:13:17.700
accurate enough.

00:13:17.700 --> 00:13:19.630
In practice, for an app like
this, you're going to want to

00:13:19.630 --> 00:13:22.720
listen for every location update
that comes through

00:13:22.720 --> 00:13:26.000
using a patent a lot like this
one, as described in the

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:30.290
Location Strategies API Guide
section "Maintaining a current

00:13:30.290 --> 00:13:33.340
best estimate." This is going to
let you listen for updates

00:13:33.340 --> 00:13:36.260
from every location source,
after which you can determine

00:13:36.260 --> 00:13:38.490
the most likely current
position.

00:13:38.490 --> 00:13:41.320
This is really important for
apps like these, where a few

00:13:41.320 --> 00:13:45.320
small offsets for a few small
seconds can turn a 10-mile

00:13:45.320 --> 00:13:47.060
jog, into a 100-mile odyssey.

00:13:47.060 --> 00:13:48.000
And you know what I mean.

00:13:48.000 --> 00:13:50.660
You've all seen someone's
hilarious social media post

00:13:50.660 --> 00:13:53.362
with a massive spike in distance
where they appear to

00:13:53.362 --> 00:13:56.760
have jogged across a river or up
a mountain range thanks to

00:13:56.760 --> 00:13:58.960
some GPS reflection error.

00:13:58.960 --> 00:14:00.630
So don't be the punchline
to a joke.

00:14:00.630 --> 00:14:04.970
Try and sanity check all of your
location results so that

00:14:04.970 --> 00:14:09.040
your users are able to get the
best possible location at any

00:14:09.040 --> 00:14:10.290
given time.

00:14:12.250 --> 00:14:14.410
Now, otherwise, the app works
in much the same way.

00:14:14.410 --> 00:14:16.400
You hit start, stop.

00:14:16.400 --> 00:14:18.900
One of the strange things is
once you hit stop, you get

00:14:18.900 --> 00:14:21.360
prompted as to whether or not
you want to save your results.

00:14:21.360 --> 00:14:22.530
Now, that should be a given.

00:14:22.530 --> 00:14:25.470
You should always save anything
the user does and

00:14:25.470 --> 00:14:29.980
give them an option to delete
something rather than an

00:14:29.980 --> 00:14:33.040
option to save it.

00:14:33.040 --> 00:14:35.760
The other thing I noticed is
that they have map pins, which

00:14:35.760 --> 00:14:39.420
look strikingly similar to the
ones in iOS, which in and of

00:14:39.420 --> 00:14:41.880
itself isn't a problem, except
that it looks a little bit

00:14:41.880 --> 00:14:46.180
weird on an Android device to
have these pins which look

00:14:46.180 --> 00:14:48.570
like they come from a different
operating system.

00:14:48.570 --> 00:14:50.680
One good piece of news for
this app, which I really

00:14:50.680 --> 00:14:53.775
liked, is that it does send
everything to a server without

00:14:53.775 --> 00:14:54.820
you having to log in.

00:14:54.820 --> 00:14:56.290
Now, logging in to the
other apps was

00:14:56.290 --> 00:14:58.170
actually a real hassle.

00:14:58.170 --> 00:15:00.710
It took a lot of time and
effort, having to exchange

00:15:00.710 --> 00:15:03.270
credentials, create accounts,
send email addresses, all this

00:15:03.270 --> 00:15:05.930
sort of stuff, whereas here,
it auto-syncs without me

00:15:05.930 --> 00:15:07.430
having to do anything,
which is actually

00:15:07.430 --> 00:15:09.830
a really nice touch.

00:15:09.830 --> 00:15:11.890
Now, while I was navigating
around this app, I actually

00:15:11.890 --> 00:15:14.320
noticed a couple of
strange artifacts.

00:15:14.320 --> 00:15:16.930
And one is the way that they
are using a web view to

00:15:16.930 --> 00:15:18.210
present a lot of
their screens.

00:15:18.210 --> 00:15:20.790
And that in and of itself
is perfectly fine.

00:15:20.790 --> 00:15:22.220
There's no problem with that.

00:15:22.220 --> 00:15:25.150
But the implementation of the
way that they've done it is

00:15:25.150 --> 00:15:26.770
making the zoom controls become

00:15:26.770 --> 00:15:28.770
visible at various times.

00:15:28.770 --> 00:15:31.360
Now, you can make sure that you
turn off both the built-in

00:15:31.360 --> 00:15:33.710
zoom controls and the visibility
of the on-screen

00:15:33.710 --> 00:15:38.160
zoom, the ability to pinch zoom
as well as the ability to

00:15:38.160 --> 00:15:41.380
zoom using the controls by
turning off the zoom controls.

00:15:41.380 --> 00:15:44.290
That should be enough to
make it all go away.

00:15:44.290 --> 00:15:46.390
But if you hit both of these
methods here, then that will

00:15:46.390 --> 00:15:49.210
definitely make sure that there
are no ability for the

00:15:49.210 --> 00:15:52.830
user to zoom on a display which
you've clearly designed

00:15:52.830 --> 00:15:54.660
not to zoom.

00:15:54.660 --> 00:15:59.000
Another strange artifact, is
this modal dialog that tells

00:15:59.000 --> 00:16:01.580
me that my GPS result
is pretty crappy.

00:16:01.580 --> 00:16:04.480
Now, I don't want to see this
unless it's preventing the app

00:16:04.480 --> 00:16:06.610
from being able to do
what it needs to do.

00:16:06.610 --> 00:16:08.870
So you really don't want to pop
it up unless I've already

00:16:08.870 --> 00:16:11.990
hit the Start button and
definitely not randomly while

00:16:11.990 --> 00:16:14.030
I'm just navigating the app.

00:16:14.030 --> 00:16:16.310
Now, last but certainly
not least, let's

00:16:16.310 --> 00:16:19.690
take a look at runtastic.

00:16:19.690 --> 00:16:23.550
Now, leaving the strange
capitalization choices that

00:16:23.550 --> 00:16:26.340
they've made aside, they've got
a pretty good landing page

00:16:26.340 --> 00:16:27.770
on Google Play.

00:16:27.770 --> 00:16:29.830
Like Endomondo, they've used
a feature graphic that

00:16:29.830 --> 00:16:31.560
immediately makes you feel
like you understand the

00:16:31.560 --> 00:16:34.030
purpose of the product and the
sorts of people that they're

00:16:34.030 --> 00:16:35.280
marketing towards.

00:16:35.280 --> 00:16:38.670
And their logo and icon is
pretty good, though I would

00:16:38.670 --> 00:16:41.020
really love to see them lose
that rounded rectangle and

00:16:41.020 --> 00:16:43.080
choose a more distinctive
silhouette.

00:16:43.080 --> 00:16:46.090
And if you kind of look at it,
you can see that maybe even as

00:16:46.090 --> 00:16:48.500
simple as removing the blue, so
you've just got the running

00:16:48.500 --> 00:16:51.790
man on the black ribbon, would
look kind of awesome and

00:16:51.790 --> 00:16:53.450
definitely distinctive.

00:16:53.450 --> 00:16:57.750
So that's something that you
guys may want to consider.

00:16:57.750 --> 00:17:00.870
Now, once we get to the main
screen, we can see that it's

00:17:00.870 --> 00:17:04.560
actually pretty similar to
Endomondo, which is great.

00:17:04.560 --> 00:17:07.720
Clearly, there is a best
practice here, which I think a

00:17:07.720 --> 00:17:10.450
lot of these apps are going
to move towards.

00:17:10.450 --> 00:17:12.930
Straightaway, we can see what
we'll be recording, and

00:17:12.930 --> 00:17:16.099
there's a big green button to
let me know to get started.

00:17:16.099 --> 00:17:19.200
And as a bonus, runtastic also
displays details like the

00:17:19.200 --> 00:17:21.700
sunrise/sunset time, the current
weather forecast,

00:17:21.700 --> 00:17:25.140
temperature, all of which
is a really nice bonus.

00:17:25.140 --> 00:17:29.870
And in fact, those extra details
are also included in

00:17:29.870 --> 00:17:31.050
my workout data.

00:17:31.050 --> 00:17:33.840
So I can see whether it was
sunny, cloudy, hot, cold as I

00:17:33.840 --> 00:17:35.860
did each workout, which I think
is a really nice touch

00:17:35.860 --> 00:17:37.850
and provides a little
bit more context

00:17:37.850 --> 00:17:39.460
for your daily workout.

00:17:39.460 --> 00:17:41.310
And they've included them on
screen here in a way that

00:17:41.310 --> 00:17:45.250
isn't overly intrusive, which
is always a nice touch.

00:17:45.250 --> 00:17:47.680
So the functionality provided
on the main page is really

00:17:47.680 --> 00:17:50.060
similar, but they've made a
couple of specific design

00:17:50.060 --> 00:17:54.400
choices which I think risks
users falling into the "you're

00:17:54.400 --> 00:17:56.480
holding it wrong" trap,
which is something you

00:17:56.480 --> 00:17:58.530
always want to avoid.

00:17:58.530 --> 00:18:01.810
So the main thing you'll notice
here is that there's no

00:18:01.810 --> 00:18:05.190
obvious indication of what
your touch targets are.

00:18:05.190 --> 00:18:08.020
And in fact, as soon as I
started touching things on the

00:18:08.020 --> 00:18:10.160
screen, I tended to
get it wrong.

00:18:10.160 --> 00:18:12.400
So I'd hit each of
the different--

00:18:12.400 --> 00:18:16.070
like duration time things to try
and get pace or calories

00:18:16.070 --> 00:18:19.330
or anything like that and
nothing happened.

00:18:19.330 --> 00:18:22.370
And so it's not until you try
to hit the smallest touch

00:18:22.370 --> 00:18:25.430
target on the entire UI, the
tiny cog in the middle, that

00:18:25.430 --> 00:18:26.305
you get that functionality.

00:18:26.305 --> 00:18:28.640
You hit that, and then you're
able to modify them.

00:18:28.640 --> 00:18:31.600
And again, what that does is
pops up a really, really small

00:18:31.600 --> 00:18:36.240
bar of icons, which lets you
choose which of the different

00:18:36.240 --> 00:18:37.600
settings that you
want to view.

00:18:37.600 --> 00:18:40.230
So again, it's tiny, tiny touch
targets, which don't

00:18:40.230 --> 00:18:41.720
tell you what they are.

00:18:41.720 --> 00:18:43.510
And this could be a real
problem, because I'm using

00:18:43.510 --> 00:18:47.010
this app while I'm stretching,
while I'm jogging, preparing

00:18:47.010 --> 00:18:49.060
to start my exercise regime.

00:18:49.060 --> 00:18:51.980
You really want to have things
be big, easy to touch, and

00:18:51.980 --> 00:18:54.150
obvious to know what you're
going to touch.

00:18:54.150 --> 00:18:56.020
And it's kind of the same thing
here once you get down

00:18:56.020 --> 00:18:59.350
to the workout type
and activity type.

00:18:59.350 --> 00:19:01.550
It's not obvious that
they're buttons.

00:19:01.550 --> 00:19:03.850
You click on them, and
it pops up a dialogue

00:19:03.850 --> 00:19:06.150
with small text in--

00:19:06.150 --> 00:19:14.170
closely spaced, and you really
want to make sure that that's

00:19:14.170 --> 00:19:16.930
easy for people to use and easy
for people to navigate.

00:19:16.930 --> 00:19:19.000
And it's the same as the
big green Go button.

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:20.350
It's clearly a button,
but it's not

00:19:20.350 --> 00:19:21.930
actually an Android button.

00:19:21.930 --> 00:19:25.960
So all these things taken
together really puts you in a

00:19:25.960 --> 00:19:28.910
situation where you're having
to think before

00:19:28.910 --> 00:19:29.780
you can use the app.

00:19:29.780 --> 00:19:31.780
You're having to figure out
how do I get it to do the

00:19:31.780 --> 00:19:33.180
things that I want it to do?

00:19:33.180 --> 00:19:35.100
And for an app like this, where
you want people to be

00:19:35.100 --> 00:19:37.190
able to get started quickly
and easily, that

00:19:37.190 --> 00:19:38.440
can be a real problem.

00:19:43.760 --> 00:19:49.650
So once we get going, they've
again made a really

00:19:49.650 --> 00:19:50.480
interesting choice.

00:19:50.480 --> 00:19:52.690
And unfortunately, I can't
show it to you right now.

00:19:52.690 --> 00:19:56.300
But once you start your workout,
you actually have to

00:19:56.300 --> 00:20:00.280
unlock the screen before you're
able to do anything.

00:20:00.280 --> 00:20:02.310
And in fact, if you don't, so
if you just try and hit the

00:20:02.310 --> 00:20:04.750
Pause or Stop button on your
workout, you get a toast that

00:20:04.750 --> 00:20:08.500
pops up saying, you're
doing it wrong.

00:20:08.500 --> 00:20:10.060
You have to unlock
the screen first.

00:20:10.060 --> 00:20:12.210
Now, I didn't even notice--

00:20:12.210 --> 00:20:13.460
excuse me.

00:20:15.200 --> 00:20:16.810
I didn't even notice that
the first time that I

00:20:16.810 --> 00:20:17.770
went to stop a workout.

00:20:17.770 --> 00:20:20.300
I just hit Stop, turned off the
screen, and when I opened

00:20:20.300 --> 00:20:23.220
up the app later on, I noticed
that it was still going.

00:20:23.220 --> 00:20:26.050
Now, a good tip for UX general
is that if you're using a

00:20:26.050 --> 00:20:28.140
toast to tell your users that
they should have done

00:20:28.140 --> 00:20:31.550
something else when they did
what they did, you're probably

00:20:31.550 --> 00:20:34.130
the one doing it wrong
rather than them.

00:20:34.130 --> 00:20:36.080
So it's really important to
figure out how users are

00:20:36.080 --> 00:20:38.130
actually using your app
and make sure that you

00:20:38.130 --> 00:20:39.020
optimize for that.

00:20:39.020 --> 00:20:41.190
In this case, they've made the
assumption that the most

00:20:41.190 --> 00:20:43.540
likely thing that may happen
is a user will accidentally

00:20:43.540 --> 00:20:45.290
stop something on the screen.

00:20:45.290 --> 00:20:48.840
Now, for most users, chances are
they would just turn the

00:20:48.840 --> 00:20:50.700
screen off when they don't
want to touch anything.

00:20:50.700 --> 00:20:53.150
So they're better off relying
on the phone than having

00:20:53.150 --> 00:20:54.400
something built into your app.

00:20:59.680 --> 00:21:01.670
OK, so once we finish the
workout, the experience is

00:21:01.670 --> 00:21:03.420
pretty great.

00:21:03.420 --> 00:21:05.200
From this point onwards,
I probably prefer

00:21:05.200 --> 00:21:06.910
runtastic to Endomondo.

00:21:06.910 --> 00:21:09.190
The contextual information you
get around things like

00:21:09.190 --> 00:21:14.090
weather, relative speed, the
way that they display your

00:21:14.090 --> 00:21:17.740
speed along your track on
the map is really great.

00:21:17.740 --> 00:21:20.810
There is an option there to
choose between Save and Done

00:21:20.810 --> 00:21:22.010
once you've finished
a workout which is

00:21:22.010 --> 00:21:23.050
a little bit confusing.

00:21:23.050 --> 00:21:25.350
As I said before, saving should
already have happened.

00:21:25.350 --> 00:21:27.070
It should just be a
case of, yes I've

00:21:27.070 --> 00:21:28.530
finished reviewing this.

00:21:28.530 --> 00:21:31.180
Let me go back to
the main screen.

00:21:31.180 --> 00:21:32.920
Another comment I had is
that their setting

00:21:32.920 --> 00:21:34.580
screen is really complex.

00:21:34.580 --> 00:21:36.720
Again, you're sort of in this
pattern of having to really

00:21:36.720 --> 00:21:39.560
read a lot of text to figure out
how to do stuff, which is

00:21:39.560 --> 00:21:42.920
something you should try and
avoid in apps like this.

00:21:42.920 --> 00:21:47.640
Now, the next few points apply
to more than just runtastic.

00:21:47.640 --> 00:21:50.150
So I want to make sure that
the shame gets applied

00:21:50.150 --> 00:21:52.110
broadly, and the credit where
it's due as well.

00:21:52.110 --> 00:21:54.182
But I think what we're trying
to focus on here on "The App

00:21:54.182 --> 00:21:56.510
Clinic" is ways that you
can improve your app.

00:21:56.510 --> 00:21:57.900
So we're going to try to
highlight a couple of the

00:21:57.900 --> 00:22:01.890
things which could be done
perhaps a little bit better.

00:22:01.890 --> 00:22:06.230
Now, first off, both runtastic
and Endomondo have a little

00:22:06.230 --> 00:22:08.610
surprise waiting in their
overflow menu.

00:22:08.610 --> 00:22:12.060
It is, in fact, an
Exit button.

00:22:12.060 --> 00:22:15.180
Now, those of you who know me
know that my initial reaction

00:22:15.180 --> 00:22:18.110
to seeing an Exit button is
something a lot like this.

00:22:18.110 --> 00:22:20.990
I chose not to destroy
our studio room once

00:22:20.990 --> 00:22:22.190
again to make a point.

00:22:22.190 --> 00:22:25.150
But in fact, you can find my
full thoughts on Exit buttons

00:22:25.150 --> 00:22:28.600
in Android apps and why they
shouldn't exist by watching

00:22:28.600 --> 00:22:32.170
Table Flip on YouTube where
I lay out exactly why this

00:22:32.170 --> 00:22:36.320
anti-patent fills me with an
impenetrable darkness.

00:22:36.320 --> 00:22:38.360
But in some ways, I
guess I get it.

00:22:38.360 --> 00:22:40.810
These apps represent kind
of a special case.

00:22:40.810 --> 00:22:42.530
They should definitely keep
running while they're in the

00:22:42.530 --> 00:22:43.520
background.

00:22:43.520 --> 00:22:45.710
And they all do use
notifications to let us know

00:22:45.710 --> 00:22:48.110
that that's exactly
what's happening.

00:22:48.110 --> 00:22:52.780
So given that, they have two
choices to figure out what the

00:22:52.780 --> 00:22:54.440
right use case is.

00:22:54.440 --> 00:22:58.940
Both of them involve getting rid
of something called Exit.

00:22:58.940 --> 00:23:01.310
They need to decide if they
are more like turn-by-turn

00:23:01.310 --> 00:23:04.080
navigation or if they're more
like a music player.

00:23:04.080 --> 00:23:05.880
Now, for the sake of argument,
I'm going to say that they

00:23:05.880 --> 00:23:09.300
should be more like music
players, which really means

00:23:09.300 --> 00:23:11.320
that I only want to see
a notification.

00:23:11.320 --> 00:23:13.160
I only want the app to continue
to run in the

00:23:13.160 --> 00:23:15.610
background while I'm
doing the work.

00:23:15.610 --> 00:23:19.440
So as soon as I hit Play or
Start, then by all means, pop

00:23:19.440 --> 00:23:22.670
up a notification, start an
ongoing service to make sure

00:23:22.670 --> 00:23:24.560
that the app doesn't go away.

00:23:24.560 --> 00:23:27.110
But then as soon as I hit Stop,
as soon as my workout is

00:23:27.110 --> 00:23:29.350
finished, then I want the
app to behave just

00:23:29.350 --> 00:23:30.010
as any other app.

00:23:30.010 --> 00:23:33.100
So hitting Home or hitting Back
out of the app should

00:23:33.100 --> 00:23:36.440
take it out of memory, should
stop GPS updates, and just

00:23:36.440 --> 00:23:38.470
basically give me my phone back
as though the app was

00:23:38.470 --> 00:23:39.420
never running.

00:23:39.420 --> 00:23:41.980
At the moment, you have this
tendency of like I just opened

00:23:41.980 --> 00:23:45.690
the app, checked it out, and I
have this icon saying or this

00:23:45.690 --> 00:23:49.440
notification saying, hey,
actually, it's still running.

00:23:49.440 --> 00:23:51.070
And that's not a great
user experience.

00:23:51.070 --> 00:23:53.260
I don't want to have to figure
out how to make it stop.

00:23:53.260 --> 00:23:57.710
I already did make it stop
by ending my workout.

00:23:57.710 --> 00:24:00.220
While we're talking about
notifications, I think there's

00:24:00.220 --> 00:24:02.940
really a fantastic opportunity
to make these notifications

00:24:02.940 --> 00:24:04.190
even more useful.

00:24:07.040 --> 00:24:10.610
Now, at the moment, all three
of the apps have a simple

00:24:10.610 --> 00:24:12.590
"click here to return to the
app" text within the

00:24:12.590 --> 00:24:14.040
notification.

00:24:14.040 --> 00:24:16.210
Now, why not be a little
bit more adventurous?

00:24:16.210 --> 00:24:19.220
I'd love to see rich
notifications with actions

00:24:19.220 --> 00:24:21.790
that let me pause or end my
workout directly from the

00:24:21.790 --> 00:24:23.190
notification shade.

00:24:23.190 --> 00:24:26.460
I'd also love to see some more
details on my workout here,

00:24:26.460 --> 00:24:28.700
things like duration,
distance traveled.

00:24:28.700 --> 00:24:31.250
Basically anything that I've
selected to look at on the app

00:24:31.250 --> 00:24:34.340
home screen, why not stick it
in the notification as well?

00:24:34.340 --> 00:24:36.660
I think that really would
present a really rich

00:24:36.660 --> 00:24:39.060
experience for your users.

00:24:39.060 --> 00:24:41.490
And in fact, when we looked at
stopwatch apps just a few

00:24:41.490 --> 00:24:44.290
weeks ago, we saw a few examples
of rich notifications

00:24:44.290 --> 00:24:47.350
being used to great effect,
where you could basically use

00:24:47.350 --> 00:24:49.360
the entire stopwatch app without
actually having to

00:24:49.360 --> 00:24:51.420
launch the app.

00:24:51.420 --> 00:24:52.950
The other thing missing
from all three apps

00:24:52.950 --> 00:24:54.130
was a tablet layout.

00:24:54.130 --> 00:24:57.240
In fact, only RunKeeper even
supported the option of using

00:24:57.240 --> 00:24:59.260
the app in landscape mode.

00:24:59.260 --> 00:25:01.390
Now, I know that these apps were
originally created with

00:25:01.390 --> 00:25:02.490
the thought of having a fitness

00:25:02.490 --> 00:25:04.120
companion on your phone.

00:25:04.120 --> 00:25:06.870
I'm sure no one really imagined
strapping a Nexus 7

00:25:06.870 --> 00:25:08.510
to your arm as you go jogging.

00:25:08.510 --> 00:25:10.352
But what about using
it at the gym or if

00:25:10.352 --> 00:25:11.420
you're using it rowing?

00:25:11.420 --> 00:25:15.640
Then suddenly, a tablet isn't
quite as ridiculous an option.

00:25:15.640 --> 00:25:19.470
Now step one is creating a great
responsive design that

00:25:19.470 --> 00:25:21.630
means that the app will work
great on whatever device I

00:25:21.630 --> 00:25:23.180
happen to be using no
matter what the

00:25:23.180 --> 00:25:25.180
orientation or screen size.

00:25:25.180 --> 00:25:27.350
So that's where I'd start,
really just make sure that I

00:25:27.350 --> 00:25:31.070
can use the app in a way that
doesn't frustrate me on a

00:25:31.070 --> 00:25:32.780
tablet device.

00:25:32.780 --> 00:25:36.700
Step two is creating a great
tablet-specific experience.

00:25:36.700 --> 00:25:39.890
Now, even if I'm not planning
to take my Nexus 10 rowing,

00:25:39.890 --> 00:25:42.210
I'd love to go through my
workouts while I'm sitting on

00:25:42.210 --> 00:25:44.770
my couch not working out.

00:25:44.770 --> 00:25:47.270
Whether that's reviewing the
tracks I've run, analyzing the

00:25:47.270 --> 00:25:50.460
data, sort of doing all that
stuff to figure out what is my

00:25:50.460 --> 00:25:54.090
fitness level, all of that stuff
will be fantastic to do

00:25:54.090 --> 00:25:55.630
directly on a tablet.

00:25:55.630 --> 00:25:57.630
And in fact, that's one of
the things that mint.com

00:25:57.630 --> 00:25:59.710
discovered when they created
an optimized tablet

00:25:59.710 --> 00:26:00.720
experience.

00:26:00.720 --> 00:26:03.570
It turns out that tablet users
are more deeply engaged and

00:26:03.570 --> 00:26:06.610
more likely to spend time
within the app.

00:26:06.610 --> 00:26:10.580
So Mint responded by creating
a richer experience,

00:26:10.580 --> 00:26:13.940
specifically for tablet users
designed around data analysis

00:26:13.940 --> 00:26:14.940
rather than data entry.

00:26:14.940 --> 00:26:17.460
So whereas on the Mint phone
app you'd go through and

00:26:17.460 --> 00:26:21.030
actually put in all of your
purchases, keep track of your

00:26:21.030 --> 00:26:23.840
budget, within the tablet app
you would be able to go

00:26:23.840 --> 00:26:26.030
through and see exactly where
you've been spending money and

00:26:26.030 --> 00:26:27.020
do that deep analysis.

00:26:27.020 --> 00:26:29.110
And I think that there's really
an opportunity for

00:26:29.110 --> 00:26:31.690
these apps to do something
similar to drive their user

00:26:31.690 --> 00:26:33.100
engagement and really
get people

00:26:33.100 --> 00:26:34.350
addicted to their service.

00:26:36.640 --> 00:26:39.700
So before we sign off, let's
take a quick look at the

00:26:39.700 --> 00:26:42.220
prescriptions that we have for
each app to help them move

00:26:42.220 --> 00:26:45.220
towards a pure Android
experience.

00:26:45.220 --> 00:26:46.800
So we'll start off
with Endomondo.

00:26:46.800 --> 00:26:49.280
So first off, kill
the Exit button.

00:26:49.280 --> 00:26:52.150
It should keep running
only while

00:26:52.150 --> 00:26:54.160
we're tracking a workout.

00:26:54.160 --> 00:26:56.200
They've actually got
kind of a bug.

00:26:56.200 --> 00:26:58.810
So I made a note to say that
they have an issue with their

00:26:58.810 --> 00:27:02.590
navigation drop-down list on
their homepage, where it

00:27:02.590 --> 00:27:04.890
doesn't have a drop-down icon
to tell you it's a list.

00:27:04.890 --> 00:27:07.960
Now, as it happens, that doesn't
seem to be the case on

00:27:07.960 --> 00:27:08.730
all devices.

00:27:08.730 --> 00:27:12.330
So that's just a bug
to take a look at.

00:27:12.330 --> 00:27:14.550
Similarly, the settings that
you've got within the

00:27:14.550 --> 00:27:17.120
navigation drop-down should be
in the overflow menu rather

00:27:17.120 --> 00:27:22.510
than within the main activities
navigation.

00:27:22.510 --> 00:27:24.190
No tablet view, forced
portrait--

00:27:24.190 --> 00:27:26.120
please don't ever force
portrait mode.

00:27:26.120 --> 00:27:29.450
I would like to use my tablet in
landscape mode, and as soon

00:27:29.450 --> 00:27:32.350
as you lock it to portrait, I
feel like you're basically

00:27:32.350 --> 00:27:34.500
saying you can't use
this app on the

00:27:34.500 --> 00:27:36.470
device that you're using.

00:27:36.470 --> 00:27:37.600
And it's a 7-meg download.

00:27:37.600 --> 00:27:39.770
I'm not entirely sure why
it's a 7-meg download.

00:27:39.770 --> 00:27:42.280
That seems like a lot for
what the app is doing.

00:27:42.280 --> 00:27:45.200
So maybe consider what you're
packaging in there and how

00:27:45.200 --> 00:27:49.990
many of those assets you need
to have on the device.

00:27:49.990 --> 00:27:52.960
In terms of runtastic pro,
10-meg download.

00:27:52.960 --> 00:27:53.620
Seriously?

00:27:53.620 --> 00:27:54.760
Why are these apps so big?

00:27:54.760 --> 00:27:57.350
It feels like you could drop a
lot of that without having to

00:27:57.350 --> 00:27:59.550
lose a lot of the assets
that you're using.

00:27:59.550 --> 00:28:02.630
The fact that it takes five
clicks to get to the beginning

00:28:02.630 --> 00:28:05.500
